    <stitle>10 SPEED TRANSMISSIONS SPICER AUTOMATE-2 - REMOVE - RANGE CASE (FIGURES6 AND7)</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="IDcomponent" graphiccount="35">
        <title>RANGE CASE (FIGURES
            <hotlnk xrefid="f1302206">6</hotlnk>
            AND
            <hotlnk xrefid="f1302207">7</hotlnk>)
        </title>
        <figure id="f1302206" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1302206" filename="../figg13/G1302206.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 6. Range Case - Exploded View</caption>
        </figure>
        <figure id="f1302207" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1302207" filename="../figg13/G1302207.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 7. Range Case Gears</caption>
        </figure>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>It is possible to service the range case without removing the entire unit from the vehicle. If the
                    truck is a conventional model, refer to
                    <hotlnk document="s13022x_8.xml" xrefid="x1302201">Procedure for Conventional Vehicles</hotlnk>. If
                    the truck is a cabover model, refer to
                    <hotlnk document="s13022x_8.xml" xrefid="x1302202">Procedure for Cabover Vehicles</hotlnk>. If the
                    entire transmission is to be serviced, follow the instructions given below.
                </para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <specpara>
            <warning>
                <para>When draining the transmission prior to working on it, be careful to let the unit cool down first.
                    Otherwise, hot transmission fluid could cause burns.
                </para>
            </warning>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Once the unit is cool, drain the transmission fluid. Remove the upper tower assembly, gasket
                and air lines while the unit is installed in the vehicle (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302208">Figure 8</hotlnk>). (It is shown here on a bench for illustration purposes
                only.)
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1302208" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1302208" filename="../figg13/G1302208.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 8. Remove Range Case</caption>
        </figure>
        <specpara>
            <warning>
                <para>Turn off and bleed the air system to prevent air lines from whipping.</para>
            </warning>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">To remove an air line from a fitting like the one shown in
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302209">Figure 9</hotlnk>, push the bushing down with a small screwdriver or your
                fingernail and pull the tubing.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1302209" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1302209" filename="../figg13/G1302209.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 9. Air Line Removal</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">The same procedure applies to the fitting shown in
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302210">Figure 10</hotlnk>
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1302210" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1302210" filename="../figg13/G1302210.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 10. Air Line Fitting</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the upper tower assembly (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302211">Figure 11</hotlnk>). Continue by removing the lower tower assembly, gasket and
                air lines through the cab floor.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1302211" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1302211" filename="../figg13/G1302211.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 11. Upper Tower Assembly Removal</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Set the transmission on a bench. Remove the air control valve and gasket (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302212">Figure 12</hotlnk>).
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1302212" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1302212" filename="../figg13/G1302212.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 12. Air Control Valve &#38; Gasket</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the three air control valve interlock pins (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302213">Figure 13</hotlnk>).
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1302213" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1302213" filename="../figg13/G1302213.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 13. Three Air Control Interlock Pins</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the backup light switch and pin (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302214">Figure 14</hotlnk>).
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1302214" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1302214" filename="../figg13/G1302214.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 14. Backup Light Switch &#38; Pin</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the automatic rail poppet insert, spring and poppet ball (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302215">Figure 15</hotlnk>).
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1302215" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1302215" filename="../figg13/G1302215.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 15. Automatic Rail Poppet Insert</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">If the unit is equipped with a neutral safety switch, remove it (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302216">Figure 16</hotlnk>). Also remove the pin underneath the switch.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1302216" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1302216" filename="../figg13/G1302216.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 16. Neutral Safety Switch</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the interlock plate and retainer. Also remove the three springs and poppet balls (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302217">Figure 17</hotlnk>). Note that the spring that is removed from the overdrive
                shift rail poppet hole has less tension than the other two springs.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1302217" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1302217" filename="../figg13/G1302217.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 17. Remove Interlock Plate &#38; Retainer</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the two clutch housing bolts from the case (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302218">Figure 18</hotlnk>). Also remove all but four clutch housing-to-case bolts.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1302218" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1302218" filename="../figg13/G1302218.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 18. Clutch Housing Bolt Removal</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Attach a bracket or lift hook to the range section of the transmission (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302219">Figure 19</hotlnk>). Secure with bolts which are firmly hand-tightened.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1302219" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1302219" filename="../figg13/G1302219.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 19. Lift Hook To Range Section</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Stand the transmission on end on a work bench that contains a hole for the input shaft (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302220">Figure 20</hotlnk>).
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1302220" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1302220" filename="../figg13/G1302220.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 20. Transmission Standing On End</caption>
        </figure>
        <specpara>
            <warning>
                <para>When moving heavy parts, use a chain hoist to help prevent personal injury.</para>
            </warning>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the electric speedometer sensing unit and end yoke or flange (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302221">Figure 21</hotlnk>).
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1302221" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1302221" filename="../figg13/G1302221.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 21. Electric Speedometer Sensing Unit</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the rear countershaft bearing retainer cap and the air regulator valve (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302222">Figure 22</hotlnk>).
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1302222" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1302222" filename="../figg13/G1302222.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 22. Regulator Valve</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the second rear countershaft bearing retainer cap (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302223">Figure 23</hotlnk>). The oil cooler pump will be removed with the countershaft
                bearing retainer cap. Remove the oil cooler pump hose and clean with solvent. If the hose or filter is
                damaged, replace it.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1302223" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1302223" filename="../figg13/G1302223.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 23. Second Rear Countershaft Bearing Retainer Cap</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the range piston housing and piston (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302224">Figure 24</hotlnk>). Also remove and replace the three O-rings.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1302224" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1302224" filename="../figg13/G1302224.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 24. Replace Three O-Rings</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the output bearing cap and shims (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302225">Figure 25</hotlnk>).
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1302225" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1302225" filename="../figg13/G1302225.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 25. Output Bearing Cap &#38; Shims</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the range case bolts and lift the case from the unit (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302226">Figure 26</hotlnk>). A pry bar can be used to help separate the range case
                from the main case.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1302226" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1302226" filename="../figg13/G1302226.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 26. Lift Case From Unit</caption>
        </figure>
        <specpara>
            <warning>
                <para>When moving heavy parts, use a chain hoist to help prevent personal injury.</para>
            </warning>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">The output shaft and low range gear will remain with the case (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302227">Figure 27</hotlnk>).
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1302227" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1302227" filename="../figg13/G1302227.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 27. Output Shaft &#38; Low Range Gear</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the range synchronizer and fork assembly (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302228">Figure 28</hotlnk>).
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1302228" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1302228" filename="../figg13/G1302228.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 28. Range Synchronizer &#38; Fork Assembly</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Be aware that separating the synchronizer will suddenly release the springs (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302229">Figure 29</hotlnk>).
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1302229" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1302229" filename="../figg13/G1302229.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 29. Releasing Springs</caption>
        </figure>
        <specpara>
            <warning>
                <para>Always wear safety glasses to help protect your eyes against flying parts.</para>
            </warning>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Replace the fork clips if they are worn or damaged (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302230">Figure 30</hotlnk>). Also inspect the fork. Replace it if it is damaged.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1302230" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1302230" filename="../figg13/G1302230.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 30. Fork Clips</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the clutch drive gear and the synchronizer cup (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302231">Figure 31</hotlnk>).
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1302231" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1302231" filename="../figg13/G1302231.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 31. Clutch Drive Gear</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Lift high range gear from the case (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302232">Figure 32</hotlnk>).
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1302232" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1302232" filename="../figg13/G1302232.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 32. Range Gear From Case</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Align the valley between the countershaft teeth with the corners of the shift bar support
                bracket (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302233">Figure 33</hotlnk>). This will provide enough clearance for countershaft
                removal.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1302233" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1302233" filename="../figg13/G1302233.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 33. Alignment Between Countershaft Teeth</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Simultaneously lift both countershafts straight up to remove them (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302234">Figure 34</hotlnk>).
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1302234" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1302234" filename="../figg13/G1302234.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 34. Lift Both Countershafts</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the mainshaft reverse gear and rear thrust plate together (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302235">Figure 35</hotlnk>).
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1302235" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1302235" filename="../figg13/G1302235.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 35. Mainshaft Reverse Gear</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the countershaft reverse gears (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302236">Figure 36</hotlnk>).
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1302236" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1302236" filename="../figg13/G1302236.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 36. Countershaft Reverse Gear</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the countershaft rear bearing retainer plates and shims (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302237">Figure 37</hotlnk>).
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1302237" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1302237" filename="../figg13/G1302237.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 37. Retainer Plates &#38; Shims</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Use a soft mallet to tap the output shaft from the case (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302238">Figure 38</hotlnk>).
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1302238" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1302238" filename="../figg13/G1302238.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 38. Tap Output Shaft From Case</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the output shaft bearings from the case (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302239">Figure 39</hotlnk>). Also press the bearing from the shaft.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1302239" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1302239" filename="../figg13/G1302239.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 39. Output Shaft Bearings From Case</caption>
        </figure>
        <specpara>
            <warning>
                <para>When pressing bearings, use a shield to protect people from possible flying parts.</para>
            </warning>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">These bearings and spacers are a matched set (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302240">Figure 40</hotlnk>).
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1302240" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1302240" filename="../figg13/G1302240.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
            <caption>Figure 40. Bearings &#38; Spacers</caption>
        </figure>
        <specpara>
            <caution>
                <para>If it is necessary to replace any of these items, replace them as a set to help ensure proper end
                    play.
                </para>
            </caution>
        </specpara>
    </svcproc>
